          "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's theological watershed. 'I will hear what God the Lord will say' — the first-person singular singular suddenly narrows the communal 'we' to an individual voice, almost certainly the Levitical singer-prophet who will stand in the place of the congregation and receive a divine word on their behalf. The structural parallel to Habakkuk 2:1 is exact: 'I will stand on my guard post and station myself on the rampart; and I will keep watch to see what He will speak to me.' Both prophets stop arguing with God and wait. Both receive an oracle. The embedded warning — 'but let them not turn back to folly' — is the hinge condition. Peace is promised, but not unconditionally. The folly (kislah — presumption, moral stupidity) that brought the discipline must not be returned to. The psalm insists that the community's posture toward the coming restoration matters: those who receive it with fear (v. 9) will find salvation near; those who presume upon it and return to folly will find they have rejected the very word God spoke."
