        "number": 1,
        "title": "Remembered mercy as the ground of present appeal",
        "range": "85:1-3",
        "excerpt": "O Lord, You showed favor to Your land; You restored the captivity of Jacob. You forgave the iniquity of Your people; You covered all their sin.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a series of five Hebrew perfect-tense verbs — all completed acts of YHWH in the past. This is not liturgical sentiment but argument: the psalmist is building a case from evidence. The verbs are carefully chosen. 'Showed favor' (ratsah) and 'restored the captivity' (shevut yaaqov) point to the historical return from Babylon — the same idiom Jeremiah uses repeatedly for the post-exilic restoration (Jer. 30:3, 18; 33:7). YHWH had already reversed the judgment of the Exile. The community knows this; they are standing on the far side of that grace.\n\nBut the psalmist does not stop at political restoration. He descends to the theological root: 'You forgave the iniquity of Your people; You covered all their sin' (v. 2). Two Hebrew verbs for pardon are employed in sequence. Nasa (to lift up, carry away) is the word used in Leviticus 16 for the scapegoat bearing iniquity out of the camp — the priestly idiom of guilt transferred and removed. Kasah (to cover) is the word behind the concept of atonement's veil over sin — not removal only but concealment from divine sight. Together they exhaust the problem: the guilt is carried away, and what remains is covered. The Selah at the end of verse 2 marks a musical pause for the congregation to absorb the magnitude of what has been declared.\n\nVerse 3 names what made the forgiveness possible from the divine side: YHWH 'withdrew all Your fury' and 'turned away from Your burning anger.' Three distinct Hebrew words for divine anger appear here and in verse 4 — evrah, charon, aph — signaling that the wrath averted was not mild displeasure but comprehensive judgment. This is the God who had sent Babylon as His instrument of discipline (Hab. 1:6); He had now withdrawn that very instrument and the burning anger that sent it.\n\nThe pastoral logic of this opening is the logic of all biblical prayer: we pray from what God has done, not from what we deserve. As Spurgeon wrote on this psalm, 'The believer pleads not his own merits but God's own acts — he holds the receipt in his hand and says, You have done this before; here is the record of it.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shevut yaaqov* (restored the captivity of Jacob) — this specific phrase recurs in Jer. 30:3, 18; 33:7; Ezek. 39:25; the psalmist is invoking the prophetic promise as a completed reality. *Nasa* (forgave/lifted away) — the same root used in the Aaronic blessing (Num. 6:26) and the Servant's bearing of sin in Isa. 53:12. *Kasah* (covered) — the same root in Prov. 10:12 ('love covers all transgressions'), cited in 1 Pet. 4:8."
