        "title": "The prophetic pivot — listening, peace, and the condition of shalom",
        "range": "85:8",
        "excerpt": "I will hear what God the Lord will say; For He will speak peace to His people, to His godly ones; But let them not turn back to folly.",
        "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's structural and theological turning point, and it rewards careful attention. The first-person singular — 'I will hear' — narrows the communal 'we' of the lament to an individual voice, almost certainly the Levitical singer functioning as a mediating prophet who steps back from the congregation's petition and adopts the posture of receiving a divine oracle. The structural parallel is Habakkuk 2:1: 'I will stand on my guard post... and I will keep watch to see what He will speak to me.' In both cases, the prophet stops arguing and waits. In both cases, an oracle follows immediately.\n\nThe psalmist does not wait in uncertainty. He already anticipates the oracle's content before he hears it: 'For He will speak peace to His people, to His godly ones.' The word shalom here is not merely the absence of conflict; it is the comprehensive well-being and reconciliation that constitutes restored covenant relationship. That YHWH 'speaks' it — davar, His active word of declaration — is significant: peace is not achieved by human effort but announced by divine fiat. The God who said 'let there be light' now says 'let there be shalom,' and the declaration is the act.\n\nBut the oracle carries an embedded condition: 'but let them not turn back to folly.' The Hebrew word kislah means moral stupidity, presumption, the foolishness of returning to the pattern of sin that provoked the judgment in the first place. This warning is not a legalistic qualification of grace; it is the pastoral realism that every authentic promise of God includes. The peace God speaks is for 'His godly ones' — the chasidim, those defined by covenant loyalty. Those who receive the oracle of peace as license to resume the folly that caused the crisis have not received it at all. As Peter Davids observes on a structurally analogous warning in James 1:8, double-mindedness disqualifies a person from the very provision God announced — not because God withdrew it, but because the divided heart refuses what is offered.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chasidim* (His godly ones) — from chesed; these are the covenant-loyal, the ones whose character corresponds to YHWH's own. *Shalom* (peace) — comprehensive wholeness: the right ordering of all relationships, material, relational, and spiritual. *Kislah* (folly) — moral stupidity, presumptuous sin; different from wisdom's opposite (*nabal*) — this is the folly of deliberate return to known sin."
